<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-special-matrices"
    xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Special Matrices</title>

    <introduction xml:id="special-matrices">
        <p>
            Some matrices occur frequently enough to be given special names:
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <idx>
                            <h>Matrices</h>
                            <h>Zero Matrix</h>
                        </idx>
                        The <em>zero matrix</em> contains only zeros and acts as the additive identity.
                    </p>
                    <sage>
                        <input>
                            # 3x3 zero matrix
                            zero_matrix(3)
                        </input>
                    </sage>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <idx>
                            <h>Matrices</h>
                            <h>Diagonal Matrix</h>
                        </idx>
                        <em>Diagonal matrices</em> are simple to multiply and often appear in eigenvalue problems
                        which we'll see in upcoming chapters. A diagonal matrix is a matrix that has all entries
                        outside of the <em>main </em> diagonal set to <m>0</m> (the main diagonal runs from the top
                        left to the bottom right of the matrix, while the secondary diagonal runs from the top
                        right to the bottom left).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This is an example of a 3-by-3 diagonal matrix constructed using the <c>diagonal_matrix</c>
                        command. Note that in a diagonal matrix the main diagonal entries may or many not be equal
                        to <m>0</m>.
                    </p>
                    <sage>
                        <input>
                            # 3x3 diagonal matrix
                            diagonal_matrix([2, 4, 6])
                        </input>
                    </sage>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <idx>
                            <h>Matrices</h>
                            <h>Identity Matrix</h>
                        </idx>
                        A special diagonal matrix is the <em>identity matrix</em>, which is a diagonal matrix
                        with all its diagonal entries equals to 1. Here is an example of a 5-by-5
                        identity matrix constructed using the <c>identity_matrix</c> command.
                    </p>
                    <sage>
                        <input>
                            identity_matrix(5)
                        </input>
                    </sage>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <idx>
                            <h>Matrices</h>
                            <h>Upper Matrix</h>
                            <h>Lower Matrix</h>
                        </idx>
                        Another two special matrix types are <em>upper</em> and <em>lower</em> matrices.
                        These are <em>triangular</em> matrix where all entries below the main diagonal
                        are set to <m>0</m> (the triangular upper matrix), or all entries above the main
                        diagonal are set to <m>0</m> (the triangular lower matrix). For a given matrix,
                        the method <c>LU()</c> returns the LU decomposition of the matrix.
                    </p>
                    <sage>
                        <input>
                            m = matrix([
                                [-8,  6, -4],
                                [ 2,  0, -2],
                                [ 4, -6,  8],
                            ])

                            _, L, U = m.LU()

                            print("L:"); print(L)
                            print()
                            print("U:"); print(U)
                        </input>
                    </sage>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </introduction>
</section>
